description: With the new good battery installed and all module switches ON and the load connected, measure the voltage directly across the battery terminals again, then measure the current drawn from the battery by inserting an ammeter in series with the battery. Compare the loaded battery voltage to the expected ~12 V and note whether the battery voltage collapses toward 0 V under load (indicating a high current path/short) or remains near 12 V with almost no current (indicating an open circuit or extremely high resistance somewhere in the supply path)., outcome='Battery voltage under load is 12.0 V, matching the expected ~12 V.  \nMeasured current draw from the battery is 11.988012 A.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=50.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_current', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> power supply module – downstream side of battery holder (supply output leads and LED branch),
description: With the 12 V battery re‑installed and the ammeter removed (return to normal wiring), open or invert the PSU module for access. Using the battery negative terminal as reference, measure: (1) voltage at the internal positive contact that feeds the outgoing +12 V cable, and (2) voltage at the anode side of the green PSU LED (before its series resistor) and at the node between resistor and LED. Compare these to the battery positive voltage to determine whether the high current path bypasses the LED branch or is before/after the PSU output node., outcome='Battery measures 12.0 V between its positive and negative terminals. The PSU output positive node, the anode side of the green LED, and the resistor’s battery-side node are all at about 0.012 V relative to battery negative, while the LED cathode is at 0.0 V. This indicates the high-current +12 V path is not present at the PSU output node and the LED branch nodes are essentially at ground potential.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=90.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> internal wiring between battery positive and PSU output / LED branch,
description: With the PSU module opened or inverted for full access, perform a detailed continuity test (power OFF, battery removed). Using an ohmmeter, measure resistance from the battery positive terminal to (a) the internal pad/contact that feeds the outgoing +12 V cable, and (b) the resistor/LED anode node. Then, with one probe on battery positive, probe around the PCB traces and any internal wiring to locate where continuity is lost (e.g., cracked PCB trace, unsoldered lug, open fuse or link). Also check for unexpected low-resistance paths from battery positive to battery negative inside the PSU. Record which segment between battery positive and the PSU output/LED node is open or abnormal., outcome='Battery positive has solid continuity to the PSU Output Cable (+), the PSU Green LED Resistor, and the Battery Internal Resistor, and a 1000 Ω path to the PSU Status LED (green), all matching nominal values.  \nThere is an expected low-resistance path (short) between battery positive and the PSU Output Cable (−) inside the PSU, indicating both PSU output cables share the same node as the battery during this test.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=260.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
